Can somebody comment on how to make these keys map to `<k0>` thru `<k9>` in neovim (this works fine in vim)?

From [`nvim/getchar.c:1430`](https://github.com/neovim/neovim/blob/0bce4dc54427d05ab320a88f6269a9c1b05ea899/src/nvim/getchar.c#L1430)

```
      case K_K0:          c = '0'; break;
      case K_K1:          c = '1'; break;
      case K_K2:          c = '2'; break;
      case K_K3:          c = '3'; break;
      case K_K4:          c = '4'; break;
      case K_K5:          c = '5'; break;
      case K_K6:          c = '6'; break;
      case K_K7:          c = '7'; break;
      case K_K8:          c = '8'; break;
      case K_K9:          c = '9'; break;
```

I've narrowed it down to at least this fact: the following line in `tk_getkeys` reports keypad input 9 as `9` (I'm basing this on a call to `termkey_strfkey`, but the same call in the demo program correctly yields `<KP9>`):

```
tk_getkey(input->tk, &key, force)
```

I tried setting `TERMKEY_FLAG_CONVERTKP` (though I don't really understand its description) but it did not have any apparent effect:

```
termkey_set_flags(rv->tk, curflags | TERMKEY_FLAG_CONVERTKP);
```

Note that the termkey demo program uses `termkey_waitkey` whereas we are using the lower-level `termkey_getkey`. [update: makes no difference; `termkey_waitkey` also returns `9` for KP9 input]

libtermkey demo output:

```
getkey(force=0): buffer 1b 4f 79 
Driver terminfo yields TERMKEY_RES_NONE 
Driver CSI yields TERMKEY_RES_KEY
Keysym sym=51(KP9) mod=+00
Key <KP9>
```

---

Vim: if I enter KP9 sequence after `<C-V>` in insert mode, input is the literal byte sequence:

```
^[Oy
```

that is, `<esc>` followed by `4f 79`, which matches libtermkey demo above (`buffer 1b 4f 79`).

Neovim: if I enter KP9 sequence after `<C-V>` in insert mode, input is a literal `<tab>` (ASCII code for tab is 0x9).

Another example: 
- `i<c-v><up>` in Vim inserts `^[OA` (byte sequence `1b 4f 41`).
- `i<c-v><up>` in Nvim inserts `<Up>` (4-characters `< U p >`).

Clearly, our escape handling is getting in the way of some functions that do not want  or need the escape handling. Input after `<C-V>` should not be subject to timing, for example.

---

